<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_quad_ring_units" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Unit groups of quadratic extensions</title>
<theorem xml:id="th_quad_ring_units_imaginary">
<title>Unit groups of imaginary quadratic extensions</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>d</m> be a negative squarefree integer, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. 
<ul>
    <li>
        <p>
            If <m>d=-1</m>, then <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*=\{1,-1,i,-i\}</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            If <m>d=-3</m>, then <m>\mathcal{O}_K=\{1,\omega, \dots, \omega^5\}</m>, where 
            <m>\omega=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}i=e^{\pi i/3}</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            If <m>d=-2</m> or <m>d\leq -5</m>, then <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*=\{1,-1\}</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ul>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<remark>
<p>
    It is worth pointing out a notational trick employed in the proof above that allows us to avoid the annoyance of dealing with the different descriptions of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> depending on whether or not <m>d\equiv 1\pmod 4</m>. Namely, we make the simple observation that in all cases (<m>d\equiv 1,2,3\pmod 4</m>), an arbitrary element of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> can be written as 
    <md>
        <mrow>\alpha \amp =\frac{m}{2}+\frac{n}{2}\sqrt{d}</mrow>
    </md>
    for some integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m>. Of course, it is not the case that any choice of integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> will produce an element of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> in this way. In fact, if <m>d\equiv 2,3\pmod 4</m>, then we must have <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> even; and if <m>d\equiv 1\pmod 4</m>, we must have <m>m\equiv n\pmod 2</m>. However, for many of the arguments below, the exact nature of of the coefficients in our expression of <m>\alpha</m> is not important. When this is the case, we will simply write <md>\alpha=q_1+q_2\mathcal{d}</md>, with the assumption that <m>q_1</m> and <m>q_2</m> are at worst half-integers. 
</p>
    
</remark>
<p>
    We see then that the story of the unit groups of imaginary quadratic rings of integers is quite a simple one. Things are significantly more complicated for the real quadratic extensions. 
</p>
<example xml:id="eg_quad_ring_units_2">
<title>Units of <m>\Z[\sqrt{2}]</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{2})</m>.  Show that <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*</m> is infinite. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>

</p>
</solution>
</example>
<theorem xml:id="th_quad_rings_units">
<title>Unit group of real quadratic extensions</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be a positive squarefree integer, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            There is a unit <m>u\in \mathcal{O}_K^*</m> such that <m>u\ne \pm 1</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            The set <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*\cap (1,\infty)</m> has a least element <m>\epsilon_d</m>, and we have 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow>\mathcal{O}_K^* \amp =\{\pm \epsilon_d^n\mid n\in \Z\}</mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>
<definition xml:id="d_fund_unit">
<title>Fundamental unit</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be a positive squarefree integer, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. A <term>fundamental unit</term> of <m>\mathcal{O}_K</m> is an element <m>\epsilon\in \mathcal{O}_K^*</m> such that <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*=\{\pm \epsilon^n\mid n\}</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<p>
    We defer the proof of (1) of <xref ref="th_quad_rings_units"/> until the next section. That argument will involve an analysis of the <em>Pell equation</em> <m>x^2-dy^2=1</m>. For now, we will content ourselves with showing how (1) implies (2). For this, the following lemma will come in handy. 
</p>
<lemma xml:id="lem_quad_ring_units">
    <title>Units in <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*\cap (1,\infty)</m></title>
    <statement>
        <p>
        Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be a positive squarefree integer, and let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>. Assume <m>u=q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}\in \mathcal{O}_K^*-\{1,-1\}</m>.
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    We have 
                    <md number="yes">
                        <mrow xml:id="eq_quad_ring_partition">u \amp \in (-\infty, -1)\cup (-1,0)\cup (0,1)\cup (1,\infty) </mrow>
                    </md>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    We have 
                    <md number="yes">
                        <mrow> \{u,-u,u^{-1},-u^{-1}\} \amp = \{q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}, q_1-q_2\sqrt{d},-q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}, -q_1-q_2\sqrt{d}\}\subseteq \mathcal{O}_K^* </mrow>
                    </md>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Each interval appearing in <xref ref="eq_quad_ring_partition"/> contains exactly one of the elements <m>\{u,-u,u^{-1},-u^{-1}\}</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>u\in (1,\infty)</m> if and only if <m>q_1</m> and <m>q_2</m> are positive. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
            
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Since <m>d&gt; 0</m>, <m>K\subseteq \R</m>. Since <m>u\in \mathcal{O}_K^*</m>, we must have <m>u\ne 0</m>. And by assumption we have <m>u\ne \pm 1</m>. It follows that <m>\alpha\in \R-\{-1,1,0\}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                     Clearly <m>u\in \mathcal{O}_K^*</m> if and only if <m>-u\in \mathcal{O}_K^*</m>. Furthermore, since <m>u\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> if and only if <m>\overline{u}\in \mathcal{O}_K</m>, and since <m>u^{-1}=\pm \overline{u}</m>, we have <m>u\in \mathcal{O}_K</m> if and only if <m>u^{-1}\in \mathcal{O}_K</m>. Lastly, the set equality follows easily from our formula for inverses and the fact that <m>N_K(u)=\pm 1</m>.  
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        In general, for any <m>\alpha\in \R-\{-1,0,1\}</m>, we have 
                        <md>
        <mrow>\alpha\in (1,\infty) \amp\iff \alpha^{-1}\in (0,1) </mrow>
        <mrow>\amp \iff -\alpha^{-1}\in (-1, 0)</mrow>
        <mrow> \amp \iff -\alpha\in (-\infty,-1) </mrow>
       </md>, 
       and thus each of the four intervals of <xref ref="eq_quad_ring_partition"/> contains exactly one of the elements of <m>\{u, u{-1},-u^{-1},-u\}</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            First note that since <m>N_K(u)=q_1^2-q_2^2d=\pm 1</m> and <m>d\geq 2</m>, we cannot have <m>q_1=0</m>; and since <m>u\ne \pm 1</m>, we cannot have <m>q_2=0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Next,  
            since <m>u'=\abs{q_1}+\abs{q_2}\sqrt{d}</m> is clearly the maximum element of <m>\{u,-u,u^{-1},-u^{-1}\}</m>, and since exactly one of these elements lies in <m>(1,\infty)</m>, <m>u'</m> must be the sole element of <m>(1,\infty)</m>. It follows that <m>u\in (1,\infty)</m> if and only if <m>u=u'</m> if and only if <m>q_1</m> and <m>q_2</m> are positive. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
    </proof>
</lemma>
<p>
    And now for the proof that the existence of a nontrivial unit implies the existence of a fundamental unit. 
</p>
<proof>
    <title>Proof that (1) implies (2) in <xref ref="th_quad_rings_units"/></title>
    <p>
       Assume we have <m>u=q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}\in \mathcal{O}_K^*-\{1,-1\}</m>. From <xref ref="lem_quad_ring_units"/> we may assume <m>q_1</m> and <m>q_2</m> are both positive and thus that <m>u\in \mathcal{O}_K^*\cap (1,\infty)</m>. 
    </p>
</proof>
<p>
    Finding the smallest element of <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*\cap (1,\infty)</m> might actually be tricky, since we are comparing sizes of irrational elements. The next corollary simplifies things for us significantly: for elements <m>u=q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}</m> of <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*\cap (1,\infty)</m>, we can compare size simply by looking at the second coefficient <m>q_2</m>. 
</p>
<corollary xml:id="cor_quad_ring_units">
    <title>Unit group of real quadratic extensions</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>d\in \Z-\{0,1\}</m> be a positive squarefree integer, let <m>K=\Q(\sqrt{d})</m>, and let <m>u=q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}</m> and <m>u'=q_1'+q_2'\sqrt{d}</m> be elements of <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*\cap (1,\infty)</m>. We have <m>u&lt; u'</m> if and only if <m>q_1&lt; q_1'</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            As a result, the fundamental unit <m>\epsilon_d</m> described in <xref ref="th_quad_rings_units"/> is the element <m>q_1+q_2\sqrt{d}</m> of <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*\cap (1,\infty)</m> with minimal first coefficient <m>q_1</m>. 
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Let <m>\epsilon</m> be the smallest element of <m>\mathcal{O}_K\cap(1,\infty)</m>, and write <m>\epsilon=r+s\sqrt{d}</m>, where <m>r=m/2</m> and <m>s=n/2</m> for some positive integers <m>m,n\in \Z</m>. Since <m>\mathcal{O}_K^*=\{\pm \epsilon^n\mid n\in \Z\}</m>, and since <m>\abs{\epsilon^{n}}\leq 1</m> for all <m>n\leq 0 </m>, it follows that 
            <md>
                \mathcal{O}_K^*\cap (1,\infty)=\{\epsilon^n\mid n\geq 1\}
            </md>.
            Since furthermore the function <m>f(x)=\epsilon^x</m> is increasing, we have 
            <md>
                \epsilon&lt; \epsilon^2&lt; \epsilon^3&lt; \dots
            </md>.
            Thus for all <m>u,v\in \mathcal{O}_K^*\cap (1,\infty)</m>, we have <m>u=\epsilon^m</m> and <m>v=\epsilon^n</m> for some positive integers <m>m</m> and <m>n</m>, and <m>u&lt; v</m> if and only if <m>m&lt; n</m>. Let <m>\epsilon^n=r_n+s_n\sqrt{d}</m>. To finish the proof, it suffices to show that <m>r_n&lt; r_{n+1}</m> for all <m>n\geq 1</m>, or equivalently, that <m>r_n</m> is an increasing function of <m>n</m>. Since 
            <md>
                <mrow>\epsilon^{n+1} \amp =\epsilon \epsilon^{n}</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =(r_1+s_1\sqrt{d})(r_n+s_n\sqrt{d})</mrow>
                <mrow> \amp =(r_1r_n+s_1s_nd)+(r_1s_n+r_ns_1)\sqrt{d}</mrow>
            </md>,
            we see that 
            <md>
                <mrow>r_{n+1} \amp = r_1r_n+s_1s_nd \amp s_{n+1}\amp=r_1s_n+r_ns_1</mrow>
            </md>.
            Recall that since <m>\epsilon\in (1,\infty)</m>, we have <m>r_1,s_1&gt; 0</m>. If <m>r_1&gt; 1</m>, then <m>r_{n+1}&gt; r_n+s_1s_nd&gt; r_n</m>. The only other option is <m>r_1=\frac{1}{2}</m>. In this case we must have <m>d\equiv 1\pmod 4</m>. Furthermore, since 
            <md>
                <mrow>s_1^2d=r_1^2\pm 1=\frac{1}{4}\pm 1 \amp </mrow>
            </md>,
            we must have <m>s_1^2d=1/4+1=5/4</m>, from whence it follows that <m>d\leq 5</m>. But then <m>d=5</m> (since <m>d\equiv 1\pmod 4</m>), and we have <m>s_1=1/2</m>. Now we are in the very special case where <m>\epsilon=\frac{1}{2}+\frac{\sqrt{5}}{2}</m>. Since <m>\epsilon</m> satisfies <m>f(x)=(x-\epsilon)(x-\overline{\epsilon})=x^2-x-1</m>, it follows that <m>\epsilon^2=\epsilon+1</m>, and by induction <m>\epsilon^{n+1}=\epsilon^{n}+\epsilon^{n-1}</m> for all <m>n\geq 2</m>. As a result, looking only at the first coefficients of these powers, we have <m>r_{n+1}=r_{n}+r_{n-1}</m> for all <m>n</m> (and <m>s_{n+1}=s_n+s_{n-1}</m>). Since <m>r_k&gt; 0</m> for all <m>k\geq 1</m>, we see that <m>r_{n+1}&gt; r_n</m>, as desired. 
        </p>  
    </proof>
</corollary>
    

</section>